      <h2>Setting Up a Lighting Plan for Your Job Site</h2>
      <p>A proper lighting setup considers the entire site, not just where the crew is currently working. Here's a simple framework:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Ambient / General Lighting —</strong> Flood the room or area with even light. Tripod lights at each corner of the room or string lights along the ceiling perimeter work well. Aim for 50–100 lux at floor level.</li>
        <li><strong>Task Lighting —</strong> Direct bright light at specific work surfaces. A portable work light placed near the miter saw, electrical panel, or welding station. Aim for 300–500 lux at the work surface.</li>
        <li><strong>Accent / Safety Lighting —</strong> Mark hazards, stairwells, and changes in elevation. String lights along staircases and glow tape on trip hazards.</li>
        <li><strong>Backup Lighting —</strong> Battery-powered lights that automatically turn on if the main power fails. Essential for occupied job sites with limited egress lighting.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Contractor's Checklist for Choosing Job Site Lights</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Assess the environment —</strong> Indoor or outdoor? Wet or dry? Dusty or clean? This determines the IP rating you need.</li>
        <li><strong>Measure the area —</strong> Square footage and ceiling height determine lumens required. Use the guide above to estimate.</li>
        <li><strong>Check power availability —</strong> Generator, building power, or battery? Corded lights are cheaper and provide unlimited runtime. Battery lights offer flexibility.</li>
        <li><strong>Consider durability —</strong> Job site lights take abuse. Look for drop-tested models with metal or impact-resistant plastic housings.</li>
        <li><strong>Think about portability —</strong> Tripod lights should collapse for transport. String lights should wrap quickly without tangling.</li>
        <li><strong>Check linkability —</strong> Many LED string lights can be daisy-chained together. This lets you cover larger areas from a single outlet.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
      <p>The best all-around job site light for most contractors is the <strong>Zetunlo 21000 Lumen Tripod Light</strong> (4.6★) — it's IP66 rated, has three adjustable heads, a 16-foot cord, and enough output to light a large room or outdoor area. For battery-powered flexibility, the <strong>DEWALT 20V MAX LED Tripod Light</strong> (4.8★) is the top choice for cordless-tool users. And for long hallways or ceiling grids, the <strong>LED Construction String Light 100FT</strong> (4.7★) is unbeatable.</p>
      <p>Whatever you choose, remember: adequate job site lighting directly affects your crew's safety, speed, and quality of work. A few hundred dollars in proper lights pays for itself on the first project.</p>

